[{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Reverse-Mode-Automatic-Differentiation-(Scalar-support-only)","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"Development of the code in this article with proper explaination can be seen in this YouTube video.","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Tensor-type","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Tensor type","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"I start by creating a custom Tensor type which will hold the variables and the structure of the computational graph. Code can be seen in Tensor.jl file.","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"mutable struct Tensor\n\tval::Number \t\t# Value of the Tensor\n\tparents::Vector \t# Parents of the Tensor\n\tgrad_fns::Vector \t# Gradient functions wrt parents\n\n\t# Constructor to initialise the Tensor\n\tfunction Tensor(val::Number)\n\t\tnew(val, [], [])\n\tend\n\n\t# Constructor to create Tensor using operations\n\tfunction Tensor(val::Number, parents::Vector{Tensor}, grad_fns::Vector)\n\t\t@assert size(parents) == size(grad_fns)\n\t\tnew(val, parents, grad_fns)\n\tend\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Operations","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Operations","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"Next, I defined the basic operations on the Tensor type. Code can be seen in Ops folder.","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Addition","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Addition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"function Base.:+(T1::Tensor, T2::Tensor)\n\tval = T1.val + T2.val\n\tparents = [T1, T2]\n\n\t# Grad Functions\n\tdT1 = path_val -> path_val * 1\n\tdT2 = path_val -> path_val * 1\n\tgrad_fns = [dT1, dT2]\n\n\treturn Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend\n\n\nfunction Base.:+(n::Number, T2::Tensor)\n    val = n + T2.val\n    parents = [T2]\n    \n    # Gradient Functions\n    dT2 = path_val -> path_val * 1\n    grad_fns = [dT2]\n    \n    return Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend\n\n\nfunction Base.:+(T1::Tensor, n::Number)\n    val = T1.val + n\n    parents = [T1]\n    \n    # Gradient Functions\n    dT1 = path_val -> path_val * 1\n    grad_fns = [dT1]\n    \n    return Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Multiplication","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Multiplication","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"function Base.:*(T1::Tensor, T2::Tensor)\n    val = T1.val * T2.val\n    parents = [T1, T2]\n    \n    # Gradient Functions\n    dT1 = path_val -> path_val * T2\n    dT2 = path_val -> path_val * T1\n    grad_fns = [dT1, dT2]\n    \n    return Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend\n\n\nfunction Base.:*(n::Number, T2::Tensor)\n    val = n * T2.val\n    parents = [T2]\n    \n    # Gradient Functions\n    dT2 = path_val -> path_val * n\n    grad_fns = [dT2]\n    \n    return Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend\n\n\nfunction Base.:*(T1::Tensor, n::Number)\n    val = T1.val * n\n    parents = [T1]\n    \n    # Gradient Functions\n    dT1 = path_val -> path_val * n\n    grad_fns = [dT1]\n    \n    return Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Power","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Power","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"function Base.:^(T::Tensor, n::Number)\n\tval = T.val^n\n\tparents = [T]\n\n\t# Grad Functions\n\tdT = path_val -> path_val * n*T^(n-1)\n\tgrad_fns = [dT]\n\n\treturn Tensor(val, parents, grad_fns)\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#AutoGrad","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"AutoGrad","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"Now, let's define the autograd engine, that'll move through the graph evaluating gradients. Code can be seen in AutoGrad.jl file.","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"function autograd(T::Tensor)\n\tgradients = Dict() # Dict to hold grads of T wrt all creators\n\n\tfunction compute(node::Tensor, path_val::Tensor)\n\t\tfor (parent, grad_fn) in zip(node.parents, node.grad_fns)\n\t\t\t# Chain Rule\n\t\t\tparent_path_val = grad_fn(path_val)\n\n\t\t\t# Checking if grad present or not\n\t\t\tif haskey(gradients, parent)\n\t\t\t\tgradients[parent] += parent_path_val\n\t\t\telse\n\t\t\t\tgradients[parent] = parent_path_val\n\t\t\tend\n\n\t\t\t# Recusive call\n\t\t\tcompute(parent, parent_path_val)\n\t\tend\n\tend\n\n\t# Output Node\n\tdT_dT = Tensor(1)\n\tcompute(T, dT_dT)\n\n\treturn gradients\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/#Conclusion","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Conclusion","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Development/Scalar_AD/","page":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","title":"Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation (Scalar support only)","text":"Code is now complete to perform Automatic Differentiation on Scalars. Example Usage can be seen here.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/#Introduction-to-Reverse-Mode-Automatic-Differentiation-on-Scalars","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/#Problem-Statement","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Problem Statement","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"Differentiate f(x)=2x^3 + 3x^2 + 5x + 9 automatically for x in -5 5.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/#Solution","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Solution","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"Import jac library.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"using jac","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"Next step is to define the above mentioned cubic polynomial as a function.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"f(x::Tensor) = 2*x^3 + 3*x^2 + 5*x + 9","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"Forward pass (or computation graph generation) is just about executing the function in desired range of x values and gradient at that point can be computed simultaneously using autograd.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# Define range\nX = range(-5, 5, 100) \n# Empty lists to store value and gradients at each x value\nY = []          # Evaluations\ndY_dX = []      # 1st order derivative\nd2Y_dX2 = []    # 2nd order derivative\nd3Y_dX3 = []    # 3rd order derivative\n\n# Looping over each x value\nfor x_val in X\n    # Converting point to Tensor\n    x = Tensor(x_val) \n\n    # Evaluating the function\n    y = f(x)\n    append!(Y, y.val)\n    \n    # 1st order derivative\n    dy_dx = autograd(y)[x]\n    append!(dY_dX, dy_dx.val)\n    \n    # 2nd order derivative\n    d2y_dx2 = autograd(dy_dx)[x]\n    append!(d2Y_dX2, d2y_dx2.val)\n\n    # 3rd order derivative\n    d3y_dx3 = autograd(d2y_dx2)[x]\n    append!(d3Y_dX3, d3y_dx3.val)\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"Now I have everything I need. To verify the results I'll plot them against analytical solutions.","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# f(x)\nf(x) = 2*x.^3 .+ 3*x.^2 .+ 5*x .+ 9\n\n# 1st order analytical derivative\nf_x(x) = 6*x.^2 .+ 6*x .+ 5\n\n# 2nd order analytical derivative\nf_xx(x) = 12*x .+ 6\n\n# 3rd order analytical derivative\nf_xxx(x) = ones(size(x)) .* 12","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"using Plots","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"f(x)\nplotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# f(x) plotted\nplot([X, X], [f(X), Y], label=[\"f(x)\" \"f\"], linewidth=3, ls=[:solid :dash], title=\"f(x)\")","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"(Image: f)","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"f(x)\nplotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# f'(x) plotted\nplot([X, X], [f_x(X), dY_dX], label=[\"f_x\" \"f'(x)\"], linewidth=[3 3], ls=[:solid :dash], title=\"1st derivative\")","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"(Image: f)","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"f(x)\nplotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# f''(x) plotted\nplot([X, X], [f_xx(X), d2Y_dX2], label=[\"f_xx\" \"f''(x)\"], linewidth=[3 3], ls=[:solid :dash], title=\"2nd derivative\")","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"(Image: f)","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"f(x)\nplotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"# f'''(x) plotted\nplot([X, X], [f_xxx(X), d3Y_dX3], label=[\"f_xxx\" \"f'''(x)\"], linewidth=[3 3], ls=[:solid :dash], title=\"3rd derivative\")","category":"page"},{"location":"Examples/Simple_Scalar_Arithmetics/","page":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","title":"Introduction to Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation on Scalars","text":"(Image: f)","category":"page"},{"location":"#JAC","page":"Home","title":"JAC","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"JACobian is a lightweight Reverse Mode Automatic Differentiation library written from scratch in Julia. The journey starts with the package generation, details for which can be accessed here.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Once the package structure was in place, I created wrote the code which supports Automatic Differentiation on scalars and very basic arithmetic operations (links to Dev Blog and Example Usage). ","category":"page"}]
